{"id":108,"date":"2017-04-26T14:57:40","date_gmt":"2017-04-26T14:57:40","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/?p=108"},"modified":"2025-07-22T12:06:25","modified_gmt":"2025-07-22T12:06:25","slug":"things-that-make-your-autistic-child-different-at-school-and-at-home","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/2017\/04\/26\/things-that-make-your-autistic-child-different-at-school-and-at-home\/","title":{"rendered":"Things that Make Your Autistic Child Different at School and at Home"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Your autistic child is unique \u2014 not just compared to others, but sometimes even compared to themselves. You may notice that your child acts one way at school and another at home. They might seem quiet in class but energetic at home, or well-behaved at school but emotional in familiar spaces. These differences can be confusing, even worrying, but they are deeply human \u2014 and deeply rooted in how your child experiences the world.<\/p>\n<p>At school, your child may try very hard to \u201cmask\u201d their autism. They might work overtime to fit in, follow rules, suppress stimming (self-soothing movements), or avoid drawing attention to themselves. This effort can be exhausting. Many autistic children learn, consciously or unconsciously, to hide their discomfort, sensory overload, or social anxiety just to get through the day. As a result, teachers may say, \u201cThey\u2019re doing fine!\u201d \u2014 even while your child is quietly struggling inside.<\/p>\n<p>At home, that mask comes off. Your child may feel safer to be themselves, to express frustration, to stim freely, or to let out the emotions they\u2019ve been holding in all day. You might see meltdowns, sensory-seeking behavior, or emotional shutdowns \u2014 not because home is a problem, but because it\u2019s a sanctuary. This contrast doesn\u2019t mean you\u2019re doing something wrong. In fact, it means you\u2019re doing something right: your child feels safe enough to be real with you.<\/p>\n<p>There are other differences too. At school, social rules are strict and fast-paced, making interactions harder to decode. At home, familiar people and routines offer more comfort. Communication may be easier in one setting than another, depending on sensory input, stress, or expectations. And sometimes, transitions between the two spaces \u2014 like coming home after school \u2014 can be especially hard, as your child shifts from one emotional environment to another.<\/p>\n<p>Understanding these differences can help ease guilt, reduce pressure, and open the door to more compassionate support. Rather than expecting your child to \u201cact the same everywhere,\u201d you can begin asking: What do they need in each place to feel safe and successful? Small adjustments \u2014 like sensory breaks at school or calm-down routines at home \u2014 can make a big difference.<\/p>\n<p>The truth is, your autistic child isn\u2019t \u201ctwo different people.\u201d They\u2019re one beautiful, complex soul doing their best in different environments. The more we accept and support those differences, the more they can thrive \u2014 wherever they are.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Your autistic child is unique \u2014 not just compared to others, but sometimes even compared to themselves. You may notice that your child acts one way at school and another at home. They might seem quiet in class but energetic at home, or well-behaved at school but emotional in familiar spaces. These differences can be confusing, even worrying, but they&hellip;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":1796,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"pagelayer_contact_templates":[],"_pagelayer_content":"","footnotes":""},"categories":[16],"tags":[26,25],"class_list":["post-108","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-our-big-family","tag-parents","tag-support"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/108","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=108"}],"version-history":[{"count":1,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/108\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":2028,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/108\/revisions\/2028"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/1796"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=108"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=108"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=108"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}